Welcome to science. There something going on that cannot be explained with our current understanding of the universe around us. Einstein’s General Theory of Relativity has so far passed every test when it comes to dealing with space-time problems. I wouldn’t be surprised if the solution is a mix of new maths and discovering ways we can observe how dark matter interacts with regular matter. As scientists figure things out they’ll adjust their theories and move forward.. that’s the scientific process.
@odufaighconn no

Many things in mathematics, physics, astronomy, etc are non-observed for long periods of time existing only in the form of calculated expectation. That doesn't make them not real. Case in point, the Highs Boson. We knew for a long time that it should exist. The physics was very confident. But even up until it was discovered there were some that argued other options were more likely. The same goes for dark matter. There are individuals that argue that a modification to general relativity should be made but even those options still require something like dark matter.  It's completely possible that we may discover something that will fundamentally alter what we believe, as is the way the scientific process works. But for now a very large body of evidence and physics points to dark matter.
